300 1715 95 (Title:) 95 SB
600 1715 846 (Should basic_string have a getline\(\) function?) 846 SB
300 1764 145 (Section:) 145 SB
600 1764 640 (21.1.1.4.5 \(new\) [lib.string::getline]) 640 SB
300 1813 125 (Status:) 125 SB
600 1813 118 (closed) 118 SB
300 1862 228 (Description:) 228 SB
600 1911 1436 (As identified by Beman Dawes in lib-3367, the 20 September 1994 draft of the) 1436 SB
600 1960 1464 (WP does not include getline\(\) .  It was part of the 27 May 1994 draft of the WP.) 1464 SB
600 2009 1458 (Beman suggested that getline\(\) be reinstated with the semantics as specified in) 1458 SB
600 2058 380 (the earlier WP draft.) 380 SB
600 2156 903 (In lib-3408, Nathan Myers responded as follows:) 903 SB
600 2205 1458 (\223I\222m quite concerned about the semantics implied in the string traits.  There, it) 1458 SB
600 2254 1479 (seems to be assumed that the end-of-line character is the same for all encodings) 1479 SB
600 2303 1467 (of a character type.  But, of course, even in ASCII we see an amazing variety of) 1467 SB
600 2352 1443 (line-end conventions.  Unicode is worse, with all the ASCII control characters) 1443 SB
600 2401 852 (and \(as I recall\) two more line-end characters.) 852 SB
600 2499 1492 (\223I fear that we cannot provide internationalized getline semantics with the same) 1492 SB
600 2548 1393 (interface that we have had.  I can imagine a getline\(\) which takes the user\222s) 1393 SB
600 2597 1380 (choice of line ending, but I can imagine you may want any of the available) 1380 SB
600 2646 1341 (choices to end a line.  The locale object\222s ctype facet does not provide an) 1341 SB
600 2695 1321 (\221is_eol\(\)\222 member, and POSIX does not provide the underlying support) 1321 SB
600 2744 703 (necessary to implement it in any case.) 703 SB
600 2842 1362 (\223It seems clear to me that the getline operation depends on the character-) 1362 SB
600 2891 1463 (encoding in use, and that makes it a locale-dependent operation.  It is not clear) 1463 SB
1 #C
