300 1875 95 (Title:) 95 SB
600 1875 1450 (The error conditions are not well-specified for the find\(\) and rfind\(\) functions.) 1450 SB
300 1924 145 (Section:) 145 SB
600 1924 494 (21.1.1.4.20 [lib.string::find]) 494 SB
300 1973 125 (Status:) 125 SB
600 1973 110 (active) 110 SB
300 2022 228 (Description:) 228 SB
600 2071 699 (In private email, John Dlugosz wrote:) 699 SB
600 2120 1368 (\223The error conditions are not very well specified for the find\(\) and rfind\(\)) 1368 SB
600 2169 1219 (functions, nor do I feel that they are the most appropriate  choice.) 1219 SB
600 2267 1030 (\223My interpretation of 21.1.1.4.20 [lib.string::find] is that) 1030 SB
600 2316 1382 (      1. an empty string will be found anywhere, so will always return `pos'.) 1382 SB
600 2365 1330 (      2. passing in a pos that is too large is not an error, unlike most other) 1330 SB
600 2414 1447 (functions in this class.  Instead, it fails to match and returns NPOS. This is not) 1447 SB
600 2463 1447 (explicit, but requires careful reading of the definition to figure out.  However,) 1447 SB
600 2512 1459 (rule 2 takes precidence over rule 1, so that searching for the empty string at an) 1459 SB
600 2561 563 (illegal position is _not_ found.) 563 SB
600 2659 1428 (\223I have three problems with this.  First, making such boundary conditions or) 1428 SB
600 2708 1414 (error conditions implicit rather than explicit will mean that users don't get a) 1414 SB
600 2757 1437 (clear quick answer, and implementors may miss something and implement it) 1437 SB
600 2806 1462 (incorrectly.  I doubt many will realize that 2 takes precidence over 1 above, for) 1462 SB
600 2855 1446 (example, and may happen to get it backwards.  Second, the treatment of `pos') 1446 SB
600 2904 1391 (values out of range is inconsistant with the rest of the class.  Third, it saves) 1391 SB
1 #C
