600 1939 785 (Specification of traits class is constraining.) 785 SB
300 1988 145 (Section:) 145 SB
600 1988 542 (21.1.1.1 [lib.string.char.traits]) 542 SB
300 2037 125 (Status:) 125 SB
600 2037 110 (active) 110 SB
300 2086 228 (Description:) 228 SB
600 2135 699 (In private email, John Dlugosz wrote:) 699 SB
600 2184 1468 (\223The austerity of the traits class strongly suggests certain implementations and) 1468 SB
600 2233 1471 (prevents certain optimizations.  For a simple example, the copy\(\) function does) 1471 SB
600 2282 1433 (not provide for overlapping copies.  Say I have a string "ABr" where A and B) 1433 SB
600 2331 1422 (represent substrings of  some length, and r is unused reserve area.  I want to) 1422 SB
600 2380 1385 (insert "C" into  the string, and the length of "ACB" fits into the pre-existing) 1385 SB
600 2429 1463 (allocation  \(because C is shorter or equal in size to r\).  I can't just copy B  down) 1463 SB
600 2478 1421 (to the tail end.  Instead, I have to reallocate the whole string  and copy the A) 1421 SB
600 2527 173 (part also.) 173 SB
600 2625 1496 (\223More significantly, the find\(\) functions pretty much have to be implemented by) 1496 SB
600 2674 1398 (a brute-force approach as they are defined-- locate a place where the match) 1398 SB
600 2723 1430 (occurs.  In short, I wish the traits available were richer.  It seems inconsistant) 1430 SB
600 2772 1413 (w.r.t. copy semantics, as explained in [issue 23-017], and it is so simple as to) 1413 SB
600 2821 1363 (force inefficiencies in the implementation.  In addition, it would be nice if) 1363 SB
600 2870 1485 (additional implementation-specific stuff could be placed in the traits class.  This) 1485 SB
